From: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Subject: [PATCH] libinput-device: pick pointer focus after lazy pointer init

ensure_pointer_capability() lazily creates a seat's wl_pointer state on
the first pointer-class libinput event from a CAP_POINTER device. After
weston_seat_init_pointer() returns, pointer->focus is NULL and stays
that way until something triggers default_grab_pointer_focus - which
runs only on motion, grab change, button release, or an explicit
weston_pointer_set_focus() call.

For a wheel-only device that only emits REL_HWHEEL (no motion, no
buttons), no such trigger ever fires. weston_pointer_send_axis() then
early-returns at !weston_pointer_has_focus_resource(), so axis events
are silently dropped despite the client having bound wl_pointer and the
pointer position lying inside its surface. The user-visible symptom is
a scroll wheel that does nothing until an unrelated input (a touch tap,
say) happens to nudge focus.

device_added() in libinput-seat.c does call weston_seat_repick() at
device-add time, but that's too early: the pointer state hasn't been
created yet (init is gated on the first event from a CAP_POINTER
device, not on device-add), so the repick is a no-op against a NULL
pointer.

Re-pick immediately after weston_seat_init_pointer() so the just-created
pointer's focus is set to whatever view sits at its initial position
before any axis/motion event leaves notify_axis().

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [downstream policy]
Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 libweston/libinput-device.c | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/libweston/libinput-device.c b/libweston/libinput-device.c
--- a/libweston/libinput-device.c
+++ b/libweston/libinput-device.c
@@ -83,6 +83,7 @@ ensure_pointer_capability(struct libinput_device *libinput_device)

 	if (!(device->seat_caps & EVDEV_SEAT_POINTER)) {
 		weston_seat_init_pointer(seat);
+		weston_seat_repick(seat);
 		device->seat_caps |= EVDEV_SEAT_POINTER;
 	}
 }
